div.p:
THOUGH it is abſolutely out of the power of the ſaid legiſlative authority, to confirm the poſſeſſions


mentioned; yet, to diſcover their want of generoſity in their propoſal, I ſhall, in the firſt place, conſider what a trifling proportion of thoſe poſſeſſions could be confirmed upon their own ſtating, inasmuch, as the confirming clauſe in the article, only confirms the poſſeſſor, who being ſo poſſeſſed at the time that the New-York grant was laid, and has no reſpect to any additional poſſeſſion carried on after the grant took place: The identical words are, And being ſo poſſeſſed, were afterwards granted by New-York;

               viz. After ſuch poſſeſſion was actually made, and the poſſeſſor being ſo in poſſeſſion, at the time the grant took place, ſuch poſſeſſion ſhall be confirmed, but any later poſſeſſion cannot be included in the condition of "being ſo poſſeſſed;" for, a later poſſeſſion was no poſſeſſion at all at the time the condition of poſſeſſion took place; and conſequently, every poſſeſſion which has been begun in the ſtate of Vermont, ſince the lands were granted by New-York, muſt be loſt to the poſſeſſor, and fall into the hands of the New-York grantees, with all other uncultivated lands in the ſtate; and all our purchaſes of thoſe lands from New Hampſhire and Maſſachuſetts-Bay, fall to the ground, together with our poſſeſſions, which have been increaſed an hundred fold.
